    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-09-18T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-09-18T09:00:00-05:00" n="645"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d645">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.2222/14: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-09-18T17:00:00+03:00"
                            >September 18, 1941—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 19—2:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1686. It is reported in today’s newspapers that a recent resolution of the
                    National Defense Committee provides that beginning October 1st, universal
                    obligatory military training of male citizens of the <pb facs="0661" n="649"
                        xml:id="pg_649"/> Soviet Union from the ages of 16 to 50 shall be
                    [instituted?]. The course of training is to be of 110 hours with particular
                    attention to drilling, rifle and machine gun shooting, the throwing of hand
                    grenades, anti-gas defense and other similar activities. The purpose of this
                    training is to build up pre-trained reserves for the Red army.</p>
                <p>Commenting on the resolution in their editorials <hi rend="italic">Pravda</hi>
                    and <hi rend="italic">Izvestiya</hi> state that the Soviet-German war has
                    assumed the character of a lengthy and fierce struggle which is trying all the
                    resources of both sides. They state that the Red army must receive trained
                    reserves and point out that modern war requires skilled soldiers and not persons
                    who are simply military literate.</p>
                <p>In view of the already long hours that are being enforced in industry it will
                    probably be impossible to carry out such a program without affecting production
                    to a considerable extent. This step is doubtless a recognition of the
                    seriousness of Soviet losses and the fact that hastily trained conscripts are of
                    little use in modern war.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
